Fast-forward around twenty-five years. I had chosen not to renew a
contract so that I could spend the summer with my infant son and wife on mat leave.
What better time to buy a new camera — what with a baby who can't
refuse photos and all. I had a DSLR gathering dust, its heft stopped
it from being a "casual" camera. Time to buy something I could walk
around with and not feel like I was lugging a delicate brick. I
settled on a mirrorless camera — an Olympus E-M10, which I highly
recommend — for its portability and build. It felt so good to hold, I
vowed to take a picture with it every day.

<aside>There's only one rule when taking that picture — a rule I'll repeat to myself when I feel uninspired: Just Try. </aside>

Take a picture every day I did — for three years. My camera became
part of my wardrobe. Out for groceries? Take the camera. Dropping the
daughter off at daycare? Take the camera. Off to coffee with the wife?
Take the camera. Many days I took one quick shot, other days I took a
dozen thoughtful ones. On rainy days stuck inside I often got anxious satisfying my
daily photo fix. Yet I was always able to take a picture.

There's only one rule when taking that picture, a rule I'll
repeat to myself when I feel uninspired: Just Try. Anytime
I take that daily picture, I just need to try to do the subject
justice. It doesn't have to be a particularly good shot or inspire pride. Framing,
composition, lighting, timing — they don't have to be perfect or even
good, but they should be considered.

Looking back at three years worth of photos, it's clear that I got
better with practice. Many of what I considered to be my best shots
look cluttered to me now. Some of those old photos are still gems, but
many are ones I would treat differently now or not take at all. It's clear to
me that my "eye" has improved over the years. I also experiment more with new
techniques and have started developing new themes.

